c study of the key spatial categories of the modern geographic imagination, including orientation, cultural landscape, and geohistory. In reconstructing the emergence of geographic science and the modern semantics of geographic space, this book approaches the literary and philosophical discourses of the eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries from a radically new perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aGeographyxHistoryzGermany. 0aGeographyxPhilosophyxHistoryzGermany. 0aGeographyxPhilosophyxHistory. 0aGeographyzGermanyxHistory. 0aRomanticismxHistory. 0aRomanticismzGermanyxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804787482zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804787482423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804787482/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles